INSERT INTO `pages` VALUES (5,0,'<p><strong>Student Employees<br /><br /></strong>The Center for Campus Life employs approximately 125 students during the school year. Our goal is to provide meaningful, on-campus employment for full-time (minimum of twelve credits per quarter), currently registered RIT students. Student positions provide a source of income, flexibility of working hours scheduled around classes, and valuable responsible work experience.</p>\r\n<p>Here are some of the positions that our department hires for each year: Information Desk Attendants, Tech Crew Staff, Reservations Coordinators, Vending Coordinators, Office Assistants, Student Assistant, Communication Assistants, Staff Artists, Union Managers, Music Room Attendants, Web Assistants and a Building Assistant.</p>\r\n<p>Please visit the <a title=\"Want to work for CCL?\" href=\"http://www.rit.edu/~300www/SAGraduateAssistantships.php3\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Student Employment Office Website</strong></a> to see if we have any current openings.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Graduate Assistantships<br /><br /></strong>We employ a variety of graduate students. These nine month positions, as well as a number of other graduate assistant opportunities in Student Affairs, are posted to the <strong><a title=\"Want to be a Graduate Assistant?\" href=\"../../../ga\" target=\"_blank\">Graduate Assistant Opportunities page</a></strong> each spring.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br />Full Time </strong><br /><br />A list of all current position openings at RIT is available through our on-line <strong><a title=\"Find a job or co-op\" href=\"http://www.rit.edu/careerzone\" target=\"_blank\">RIT Career Zone</a></strong> or by calling the Job Information Line at 585-475-7095.</p>','2012-03-16 15:11:54','sbgccl','about','jobs','Employment'),(4,0,'<p><strong>Mission</strong></p>\r\n<p>The Center for Campus Life at RIT provides a campus environment which supports transformational community and individual student activities, learning and growth. This is a team of creative, collaborative and committed professionals that offers students, clubs and organizations as well as the colleagues that support them, a model for work and interactions that are appropriately challenging, passionate and fun.<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><br /> Vision<br /> </strong></p>\r\n<p>RIT&rsquo;s Center for Campus Life will use every interaction, conversation, and activity as an opportunity to both exhibit and foster individual and collective evolution as we seek to become increasingly welcoming, trusted, and respected; as an organization, within the division, and at the university.&nbsp; It is our collective organizational commitment to support, challenge, and celebrate one another in becoming the department of choice as collaborators, communicators, programmers, advisors, and advocates on a quest for achieving the greatest student experience at RIT.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Division of Student Affairs Strategic Vision<em></em></strong></p>\r\n<p>The Division of Student Affairs will lead RIT in developing the nation&rsquo;s most engaged campus community.</p>\r\n<dl><dt></dt><dd></dd></dl><dl id=\"core_values\"></dl>\r\n<p><strong><br /> In response to this initiative, the Center for Campus Life will pursue the following goals:</strong><em></em><em></em></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Improve conference room facilities&rsquo; services to promote school identity, connection, and spirit among all university users and partners.</li>\r\n<li>Pursue credit-bearing opportunities for student leadership and technical experiences provided through employment in the Center.</li>\r\n<li>Establish a mentoring program for upper year students interested in pursuing work in the field of Student Affairs.</li>\r\n<li>Explore new university technologies to personalize outreach to incoming student communities to expedite and foster meaningful connections between students and with clubs and activities on campus.</li>\r\n<li>Develop a paperless/on-line communication and service delivery system to support remote access to services and improve sustainability efforts within the department.</li>\r\n<li>Expand department use of social networking and promotion technologies to encourage broader student awareness and involvement.</li>\r\n<li>Coordinate a needs assessment of commuter student support efforts with other key divisional and university partners and provide recommendations for division and university consideration as appropriate.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>','2012-07-16 13:58:50','sbgccl','about','index','About the Center'),(13,0,'<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Welcome to the Center for Campus Life!</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I am thrilled that you are visiting us on-line, and invite you to take a look through the entire website for important and valuable information. The Center for Campus Life is here to provide assistance to each of you, as a member of the RIT community, while you seek your own unique way of contributing to or connecting with life in the extended activities\' and events\' \"classroom\"; the classroom beyond your academic environments, and designed to support and enhance your student experience.</p>\r\n<p>Through programming design, implementation, and support, our efforts aim to provide opportunities for students to connect with other students, faculty and staff. The programs and related services we coordinate meet a variety of broad and diverse needs. From helping students to create their own club to sponsoring student led events, from inviting and informing the campus about the active social environment and fraternity and sorority life at RIT to encouraging the pursuit of hobbies related to your own personal interests, the Center seeks to provide something for everyone!</p>\r\n<p>Staff from the Center also manage and coordinate services in our campus\' Student Alumni Union. The SAU is host to a variety of student and staff departments. Each of these offices is central to creating and maintaining a diverse and healthy campus community. Feel free to visit the Club Resource Center - located in the RITreat at the SAU, and the SAU Information Desk - in the first floor lobby of the SAU, to learn more about the specific departments and offices in the building, and about how you can connect with events, organizations, and staff members!</p>\r\n<p>My hope is that as you tour this website, you will learn more about the exciting and dynamic community RIT provides for students wishing to be involved at any and all levels! And, that you will see the enthusiasm and commitment our Campus Life staff has in their ultimate goal of supporting your success. If you have any questions, or would like to provide feedback about additions and updates to the site, please do not hesitate to contact me. Again, welcome, and I am so grateful for your visit!</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>Sincerely,<br /><br /> Karey T. Pine,<br /> Director, Center for Campus Life<br /> ktprla@rit.edu</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2012-05-07 20:17:18','cclwww','index','index',''),(14,0,'We all live in a yellow submarine  Or do we? adsfasdfadfazfdaqfdszsdfdsaf','2010-09-03 17:10:27','cclwww','test','about','Test Content'),(15,0,'<p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p> <br /><br /><br /><br />','2007-07-20 09:49:15','1','about','departments','Departments'),(17,0,'<p>The Club Review Board (CRB) is the student led advisory board that oversees all services, policies, and procedures that relate to Student Government\'s recognized clubs. The CRB is comprised of student representatives from a variety of SG clubs, is organized by the SG appointed CRB Chair and is advised by the&nbsp;Club Administration Coordinator and Clubs Graduate Assistant.&nbsp;The CRB meets on a weekly basis to discuss and make decisions regarding club issues.<br /><br />Some areas that the CRB has responsibility for include: the SG Club Recognition process, and many other issues as they arise throughout the year. The Club Review Board provides an opportunity for the interests and concerns of SG\'s clubs to be voiced and addressed in a positive and productive manner.<br /><br />The Club Review Board is an important piece of Student Government\'s role in RIT\'s shared governance. In addition, it is an excellent leadership opportunity. CRB members gain valuable skills in teamwork, decision-making, and critical thinking, while working to improve campus life at RIT.<br /><br />If you would like to become involved in the Club Review Board, please contact <strong><a title=\"Building Student Participation!\" href=\"../main/about/profstaff\">Center for Campus Life</a></strong>. We encourage participation from SG\'s clubs. New members are always welcome.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></p>','2012-01-09 15:31:22','sbgccl','clubs','reviewboard','Club Review Board'),(18,0,'<p>Currently there are approximately 250 active clubs, 11 Major Student Organizations, and 30 Greek Organizations on campus. RIT welcomes and embraces all of its unique, student operated clubs and organizations. <br /><br />Do you have an interest or hobby? <br />Look through the <strong><a title=\"Clubs and Organizations\" href=\"clubs/all\">clubs and organizations</a></strong> at RIT.<br />You may find a club that shares your interest. <br /><br />Can\'t find a club that you want to join? <br />Find out <strong><a title=\"So you want to form a club?\" href=\"form_club/index\">how to form a new club</a></strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Why You Should Join</strong></p>\r\n<p>For information on the benefits and management needed for successful clubs please refer to our <strong><a title=\"Club How To\" href=\"views/clubs/resources/clubhowto.pdf\">how to</a></strong> on club basics.<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Important Dates</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong>If you are part of an existing organization or looking to form one it is beneficial to have a copy of our <strong><a title=\"Important Dates 2011-2012\" href=\"docs/important_dates_2011-12.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">compiled list</a></strong> of important dates.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Club Day <br /><br /></strong>Want to meet members from a club you would like to join? <br />Club Days are 10am-4pm in the Student Alumni Union Lobby.<br /><br />Club Day Dates:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">September 21, 2012<br /></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">October 26, 2012<br /></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">January 25, 2013<br /></span></li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 10pt; font-family: \'Arial\',\'sans-serif\';\">March 22, 2013<br /></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong><br />Club Mission Statement<br /></strong><br />Student Government Clubs and Organizations exist to bring students of similar interest together and provide them with opportunities to become effective leaders. These groups enhance the quality of student life by fostering social interaction, leadership development, school spirit and an affinity to RIT. Clubs and Organizations promote activities, diversity, service and learning outside of the classroom.</p>','2012-07-16 13:54:15','sbgccl','clubs','index','Clubs & Organizations'),(20,0,'<p><strong>Not actually used!!!</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Fraternities </strong><br />Alpha Epsilon Pi<br /> Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Delta Sigma Phi<br /> Kappa Delta Rho<br /> Lambda Alpha Upsilon Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Lambda Upsilon Lambda Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Omega Psi Phi Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Phi Delta Theta<br /> Phi Iota Alpha Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Phi Kappa Psi<br /> Phi Kappa Tau<br /> Pi Delta Psi Fraternity, Inc.<br /> Sigma Alpha Epsilon<br /> Sigma Alpha Mu<br /> Tau Kappa Epsilon<br /> Triangle Fraternity<br /> </p>\r\n<!--[endif]-->\r\n<p><strong>Sororities<br /> </strong>Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority, Inc.<br /> Alpha Sigma Alpha<br /> Alpha Sigma Theta<br /> Alpha Xi Delta<br /> Delta Phi Epsilon<br /> Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.<br /> Lambda Pi Chi Sorority, Inc.<br /> Omega Phi Beta Sorority, Inc.<br /> Sigma Lambda Upsilon Sorority, Inc.<br /> Sigma Sigma Sigma<br /> Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc.<br /> Zeta Tau Alpha</p>','2012-07-24 09:48:05','cclwww','fratsorlife','chapters','Greek Chapters'),(21,0,'<p>The Student Alumni Union has an interesting history. <br />RIT\'s original campus was in downtown Rochester. According to Mr. Alfred L. Davis, Vice President Emeritus of RIT, as the school grew in enrollment, RIT\'s Board of Trustees felt that the Institute should expand and relocate. On the night of November 21, 1961, the Board voted to build a new campus in Henrietta. That same night, as soon as student leaders heard the exciting news, the Student Association (predecessor to Student Government) voted to donate $10,000 towards construction of the new campus. This donation was very significant because it came from the student body.<br /><br /> When it was time for the Board of Trustees to select a name for the new \"Union\", they gave considerable thought to an appropriate name. They wanted a name to reflect the philosophy that this building should be available for the benefit of every member of the RIT community- students, faculty, staff, alumni, and visitors alike. Second, they wished to recognize the outstanding financial contributions of RIT\'s alumni towards the Union. The name reflected the strong connection between the current RIT population and its alumni. Thus was born the name \"College Alumni Union.\" Students recently lobbied to change the name so that it may better represent the fact that students need a place dedicated for students. The Student Alumni Union name was adopted.<br /><br /> Today the SAU is a living and learning laboratory, whose services and programs promote student interaction, experiential education, and self-governance in partnership with RIT faculty and staff. <strong><a href=\"sau/hours\"><br /> <br /> <br /></a></strong><img src=\"images/link.gif\" alt=\"click link\" align=\"left\" border=\"0\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"sau/hours\">Hours of Operation</a></p>','2011-06-15 14:36:53','cclwww','sau','index','Student Alumni Union'),(23,0,'<p><strong>What can the SAU do for you?</strong><br /> <br />&nbsp;<a href=\"/main/sau/building?sort=Place\" title=\"SAU Building Services\">Building Services</a></p><p>&nbsp;<a href=\"/evr\" title=\"Register Your Event Today!\">Event Registration</a><br /> </p><p>&nbsp;<a href=\"/main/sau/vending\" title=\"Learn about RIT Vending\">RIT Vending</a><br /> </p><p>&nbsp;<a href=\"/main/sau/reservation\" title=\"Campus Life Reservations\">Campus Life Reservations</a><br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> </p>','2010-09-12 20:15:34','cclwww','sau','services','Services'),(24,0,'<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"10\" width=\"402\" height=\"219\" bgcolor=\"#cbb996\"><tbody><tr><td><p><!--[if !mso]> <style> v\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} o\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} w\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} .shape {behavior:url(#default#VML);} </style> <![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>  <w:WordDocument>   <w:View>Normal</w:View>   <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>   <w:PunctuationKerning/>   <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/>   <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>   <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent>   <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>   <w:Compatibility>    <w:BreakWrappedTables/>    <w:SnapToGrid