l.<br /> <br /> </p> 		   		<p><strong>Greek Weekend<br /> </strong><br /> Greek Weekend is a weekend set aside for fraternity and sorority members to come together to compete in athletic games, serve the Rochester community, and most importantly, have fun while doing it.<br /> <br />  </p> 		 		<p><strong>NGLA<br /> </strong><br /> The Northeast Greek Leadership Association exists to promote the founding principles and positive traditions of all Greek letter organizations through opportunities that encourage learning and leadership for the Northeast region. Hundreds of fraternity and sorority leaders from the Northeast attend the Annual Meeting each year to participate in three days of workshops, general sessions and idea sharing. Each participant&#39;s conference fee includes conference materials and programs; Thursday&#39;s welcome reception, lunch Friday and Saturday; and Saturday evening&#39;s closing banquet. Our awards program allows us to recognize the outstanding efforts of Greek governing councils and celebrate our accomplishments. RIT encourages all Greek members to attend.<br /> <br /> </p> 		 		<p><strong>Greek Housing<br /> </strong><br /> Fraternities and sororities at RIT offer a wide variety of housing options to members. Each offers different benefits for chapter members. The newest additions are the freestanding houses located on the West side of campus next to the Crossroads complex, referred to as the Greek Circle. Currently, there are four fraternities and two sororities living there. The houses offer suite-style double rooms, in-house laundry facilities, a chapter room, and a large social room adjoining a full kitchen.</p> 		 		<p>You will also find six chapters residing on the East - residence halls - end of campus. These houses are specially renovated dorm floors that offer lounges and, in some cases, large basements for chapter recreation and activities. </p> 		 		<p>A full half of the chapters at RIT do not have an &quot;official&quot; house. These groups function with either one or more off-campus apartments, or in a few cases, an off-campus house. Members find this situation beneficial because it allows them live where they want and with friends that are<br />  non-members, if desired.<br /> <br /> <strong>Greek Newsletter<br /> </strong><br /> Between The Columns, a publication from the Office of Greek Life, is a monthly newsletter highlighting outstanding individual and chapter accomplishments as well as what is happening in the Greek system. The newsletter is available online during in school session.</p>','2007-08-08 14:50:43','1','fratsorlife','programs','Resources | Programs'),(63,0,'<strong>Membership Recruitment Process, what Is It?<br /> </strong>  <br /> Recruitment is a two-way process by which members of a fraternity/sorority chapter decide who they would best like to join their organization. At the same time, you, the potential new member decides which chapter interests you the most. The recruitment process is a great opportunity to meet active members, to hear their activities, values, and ideals. However, participation in recruitment does not obligate you to join.<br /><br />    <p> <strong>How Do I Decide?<br /> </strong><br /> Each person looks for different aspects in a particular fraternity/sorority. While all chapters place emphasis on academics, some chapters are also known for a focus on athletics, community service, or friendship. Most chapters encourage a well-rounded approach. The choice is up to you. Look at all the chapters and evaluate which best meets your needs and interest.<br /><br /> </p>   <p> <strong>How Should I Act During Recruitment?</strong><br />   <br />Rule number one is to be yourself. You want to know what the chapter is like and they want to know the real you. Therefore, be yourself and do not put up a &quot;front.&quot;<br /><br /> </p>   <p> <strong>Before I Join, What Do I Need To Know?</strong><br />   <br />Joining a fraternity/sorority carries certain responsibilities. Make sure you know the entire financial obligation that is required. Costs will vary from chapter to chapter, but expenses will generally include quarterly, local and national dues as well as one time new member and initiation fees. Furthermore, you should understand all the aspects of membership that are required for initiation into the chapter. Do not hesitate to ask questions. Active members will be more than willing to help you out.<br /><br /> </p>   <p><strong>What Happens When I Become A New Member?</strong><br />   <br /> A potential new member becomes a new member when he/she accepts a bid to become a member. As a new member you will partake in an education period during which you are prepared for active membership. The length of the new member period varies. During this time you are involved in a variety of activities, all designed to enable the new members to become a part of the brotherhood/sisterhood. Such activities include becoming acquainted with your chapter&#39;s history, its goals, how it functions, and your key to its future. As each new member brings new life into the chapter, each chapter will bring something new into the life of each of you who join. Once you become an initiated member of a national fraternity and sorority, you are ineligible for membership in any other fraternity/sorority. Being a new member is a time to learn about college, your chapter, and especially yourself. However, requiring new member to engage in any type of prank or hazing activity is prohibited. If you feel you have been subject to such behavior, contact the Office of Fraternity &amp; Sorority Life at 585-475-7123.</p>','2008-09-16 12:37:25','1','fratsorlife','recruitment','Resources | Recruitment'),(61,0,'<p><strong>Why vend at RIT?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Vending at RIT is a great opportunity to sell products and services to potentially thousands of students, faculty and staff members.</p>\r\n<p>Assistance from a student organization is available during your visit to RIT. You may select or our office can assign you a sponsor group. This group will contact you a few days before your visit and help to meet your vending needs. Your sponsor group is available to help you unload and load your items, set up and clean up and to give you a break during the day. Sponsor groups are students of RIT, and therefore, they are not available to stay with the vendor the whole day due to classes, but they are expected to help the vendor as much as possible.<br /> <br /> <strong>Vending Locations</strong><br /> <br /> There are two locations on campus where venders are permits to sell. The lobby of the Student Alumni Union (SAU) is our most popular vending location. The SAU is a central place for many campus offices and activities. This is also the location of two cafeterias, Ben and Jerry\'s Ice Cream and Nathan&rsquo;s Soup and Salad; all popular and busy places for RIT students, faculty and staff. Vending at RIT is a great opportunity to reach a wide range of possible customers. Grace Watson Hall is our other vending location, located on the residential side of campus. Grace Watson houses the largest dining hall on campus and is connected to two our residence halls, home to over 1,300 students, especially during the lunch and dinner times.</p>\r\n<p><strong><strong>Cost of vending at RIT<br /> <br /> </strong></strong>Vending in the SAU is available from 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM on Wednesdays, Thursdays and Fridays only. The cost to reserve a table in the SAU is $50, however, a second and third table only cost $10 each (a total of $70 for three tables). Vending in Grace Watson Hall is available each weekday from 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM, but no tables are provided. There are a limited number of spaces so please remember to book early. Payment for vending is due the day of the reservation and can be paid in cash, check or money order. If cash is used, the exact amount must be given.<strong><br /> <br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Vendor Contract</strong><br /><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" alt=\"adobe pdf\" border=\"0\" />&nbsp; <a class=\"default_size\" title=\"Vendor Agreement\" href=\"../../uploads/agreement.pdf%20\" target=\"_blank\">Vendor Agreement</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>Prohibited vending items</strong></p>\r\n<p>The following items may not be sold by vendors:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Credit Cards</li>\r\n<li>Candles or other open flame devices</li>\r\n<li>Incense and potpourri</li>\r\n<li>Touchier style lamps, including but not limited to those that use halogen, incandescent or fluorescent bulbs</li>\r\n<li>Fog machines and similar devices</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><br /> Student/Faculty/Staff/Alumni vendors</strong><br /> <br /> If you are an RIT student, faculty, staff or alumni who is interested in vending at RIT, you may reserve tables at a reduced cost. Reserving a table/vending space is only $25 for the first table. Any additional tables (up to a total of three tables) are $5 each.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Contact Information:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Brianna Schlitt</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Graduate Assistant of Vending &amp; Program Services</em></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"mailto:cclevent@rit.edu\"><strong>cclevent@rit.edu</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>585-475-6650</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Carol Reed</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Associate Director of Building and Operational Services</em><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"mailto:Cjr2033@rit.edu\"><strong>Cjr2033@rit.edu</strong></a><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>585-475-6931</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><br /> <br /> <strong>Do you have any questions?</strong><br /> <br /> <img title=\"click link\" src=\"images/link.gif\" alt=\"click link\" align=\"left\" border=\"0\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"sau/faq\">Vending FAQ</a></p>','2012-01-19 18:11:48','bldgccl','sau','vending','Services | RIT Vending '),(65,0,'<p>Main topics are explained below in effort to answer some frequently asked questions. If you still have questions not covered in CCL FAQ please call the Center for Campus Life at 585.475.7058.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p><strong>I need to meet with a member of the CCL Staff, should I make an Appointment</strong><strong>?</strong><em><br /></em>Yes, please make an appointment. Please review the Professional Staff page to find out the office hours of each individual. You may also call the Center for Campus Life at 585.475.7058 to set up an appointment with any staff member.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>What is an Artist Request Form?</strong><br />These forms are for requesting the services of Center for Campus Life Staff Artists. You may request banners, poster, fliers, and other projects by special request. These Forms are located only online by visiting http://campuslife.rit.edu/art_request</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br />Where can I locate the</strong><strong> </strong><strong>Bathrooms</strong><strong> in the SAU?</strong><br />Bathrooms are located on the main floor of the SAU by the Fireside Lounge, upstairs on the mezzanine level directly to the right of the stairs, and on the A-level near the Ritz Sports Zone.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>How can I reserve a </strong><strong>Display Case?</strong><br />Display cases can be reserved at SAU Reservations (behind the Info Desk). </p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>When is Event Registration (EVR) open?</strong><br />EVR is open every day from 1pm to 4pm. More information about EVR can be found on the <a title=\"Event Registration\" href=\"sau/evr\"><strong>Plan Your Event</strong></a> page.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>What </strong><strong>Events on Campus are happening this week?</strong><br />Visit http://events.rit.edu for a complete list. <br />Also, CCL runs the EventsAtRIT screen name on AOL, @EventsAtRIT on Twitter, and the EventsAtRIT Facebook page.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>I lost something, where can I find the Lost &amp; Found?</strong><br />Located at: SAU Information Desk, Bausch &amp; Lomb Center Information Desk, Ellingson Hall, Department of Public Safety, Grace Watson Hall.<strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br />What is an</strong><strong> Ombudsman?</strong><br />Student Ombudsman (pronounced OM\'-BUDZ-MEN): One who investigates reported complaints from students, reports findings, and helps to achieve equitable settlements. The Ombuds office is located in the SAU, room 1110 (in the RITreat).</p>\r\n<p><strong><br />How can I get a </strong><strong>Quarterly Calendar?</strong><br />The Center for Campus Life Marketing and Publicity Team publishes a quarterly calendar of on campus events. Calendars are mailed to commuter students residing locally, distributed by Resident Advisors and Community Advocates to students in the Residence Halls, Apartments and the RIT Inn. Additional copies are available at the Information Desk in the lobby of the Student Alumni Union.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br />Who can make </strong><strong>Reservations?</strong><strong><br /></strong>SAU Reservations is located behind the Info Desk. Student groups, staff, and faculty can reserve rooms in the SAU and in academic buildings. Display cases and tables can also be reserved through SAU Reservations. The phone number is 585.475.6992 and email address is reserve@rit.edu.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>How can I get a copy of The Source?</strong><br />Source Books are available in the Off-Campus and Apartment Student Association (OCASA) Office located in the RITreat of the Student Alumni Union. <strong><a title=\"The Source Handbook Online\" href=\"../../../thesource/\">The Source</a></strong> is also available online.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><br />Student Affairs is located where?</strong><br />Student Affairs is located on the mezzanine level of the SAU.<br /><br /><strong><br />Student Conduct Office is located where?</strong><br />The Student Conduct Office is located on the mezzanine level of the SAU in room 2460.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Where can I purchase</strong><strong> Tickets?</strong><br />Tickets for major events are sold at the Gordon Field House Box Office (475-4121).</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br /><strong>Where is Vending located?</strong><br />RIT Vending is located behind the Info Desk. The phone number is 585.475.5248.<br />Hours change quarterly. More info can be found on the <a title=\"RIT Vending\" href=\"sau/vending\"><strong>RIT Vending</strong></a> page.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>How do I apply for a Graduate Assistantship for 2012-2013?</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">If you\'re looking to apply to be a Graduate Assistant at RIT, visit here to apply: <a href=\"http://www.rit.edu/studentaffairs/SAGraduateAssistantships.php\">http://www.rit.edu/studentaffairs/SAGraduateAssistantships.php</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;</p>','2012-07-16 14:01:12','sbgccl','about','FAQ','Center for Campus Life FAQ'),(66,0,'<p><strong>Large Concert</strong><br /><br />Possible Events:<br /> <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CAB Concerts- Lupe Fiasco<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Club Concerts- Mi Tierra<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Comedians- Lisa Lampanelli<br /><br /><br />Typical Equipment:<br /> <br /> <em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sound System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4 hi speakers/side<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4 subwoofers/side<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 12 stage monitor speakers<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 stage monitor control console<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 house control console<br /> <br /> <em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lighting System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 60 lights down stage on truss<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 48 lights up stage on truss<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 lighting control console<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; optional followspots<em></em><br /><br /><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" alt=\"Download PDF\" align=\"left\" border=\"0\" />&nbsp; <a title=\"Clark Gym Diagram\" href=\"docs/Gym%20Large%20Concert.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Diagram of Room Setup</a></p>','2011-10-06 13:18:07','mvr5623','techcrew','clarkgym','Room Setups | Clark Gym'),(67,0,'<p><strong>Ingle Lecture</strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />Possible Events:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganette Lectures<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cultural Spotlight Speakers<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Awards Ceremonies<br /><br /><br />Typical Equipment:<br /><br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sound System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ingle House Speaker System<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2 wireless lav/hand helds<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 podium/microphone<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; optional panel table with microphones<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; optional stage monitors<br /><br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lighting System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ingle Prefocust Lighting Wash<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Any special lighting for events may affect price of event<br /><br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Video System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ingle Projection System<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10.5\' x 14\' rear projected screen<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; switching between 2 laptops, DVD, VHS, Visualizer<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additional Video Support may affect price of event<br /><br /><br /><img src=\"images/icon_acrobat.gif\" alt=\"Download PDF\" align=\"left\" border=\"0\" />&nbsp; <a title=\"Ingle Lecture Diagram\" href=\"docs/Typical%20Ingle%20Lecture%20Event.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Room Setup Diagram</a></p>','2011-10-06 13:19:00','mvr5623','techcrew','ingleauditorium','Room Setups | Ingle Auditorium'),(68,0,'<p><strong>Fireside Dance Parties<br /><br /></strong>Typical Equipment:<br /><br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sound System</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Optional DJ CD Mixer system<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 Hi speaker/side<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 subwoofer/side<br /><br /><em>&nbsp